      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022R1 used under FDA-recognized quality management system; version-controlled input decks archived in validated document control system.",
      "rationale": "All simulation software used in this assessment operates under a documented QMS compliant with 21 CFR Part 820. Software version records, installation qualification records, and change control logs are available. Achieved level exceeds required level for this risk tier."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical benchmark suite results (NAFEMS benchmarks LE1, LE10, NL1) confirm correct implementation of linear and nonlinear element formulations used in this model.",
      "rationale": "The solver has been verified against published NAFEMS benchmark problems relevant to structural contact mechanics. Results are within published tolerances. Required and achieved levels are equal, satisfying the credibility threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between the medium and fine mesh densities; GCI < 1% for each QoI.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the pedicle screw and rod assembly. The grid convergence index for stiffness, yield force, and 40 mm force was 0.4%, 0.7%, and 0.6% respectively. The production mesh is the medium-density configuration, which is verified to be in the asymptotic range."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force residual and displacement increment norms fall below 1e-4 at each converged increment; no divergent load steps observed.",
      "rationale": "Newton-Raphson convergence was monitored across all load increments. Force residuals converged to 8e-6 and displacement norms to 3e-5, both well within the specified tolerance. No spurious contact oscillations were detected in the load-displacement output."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model setup, boundary condition application, and post-processing scripts reviewed by a second qualified analyst independent of the primary modeler.",
      "rationale": "An independent peer review of all model input files, boundary condition definitions, and post-processing scripts was completed prior to submission. Reviewer confirmed correct application of ASTM F1717 loading configuration and displacement extraction methodology. One minor annotation error was corrected; no QoI-affecting errors were identified."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Continuum elastic-plastic constitutive model with isotropic hardening is appropriate for titanium alloy pedicle screws under quasi-static bending; contact formulation captures screw-rod interface behavior.",
      "rationale": "The bilinear isotropic hardening model calibrated to Ti-6Al-4V tensile coupon data is well-established for predicting structural response of spinal implants under quasi-static loading. The augmented Lagrangian contact algorithm correctly captures load transfer at the set-screw interface. Model form uncertainty is bounded by the ensemble of three independent FEA implementations."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific tensile testing of implant-grade Ti-6Al-4V; geometric inputs derived from CMM measurements of production components.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and tangent modulus were determined from five tensile coupons machined from the same material lot as the test constructs. Component geometry was characterized by coordinate measuring machine with ±0.005 mm uncertainty. Torque preload on set screws was applied as a prescribed angular displacement calibrated from torque-angle measurements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 production constructs spanning two independent laboratories; sample traceability to lot numbers documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from production components traceable to a single manufacturing lot. Six constructs were tested at Laboratory A and five at Laboratory B. Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation for stiffness was 3.2%, confirming acceptable test reproducibility."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate ASTM F1717 protocol with documented environmental controls; multiple load levels or configurations tested.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted strictly per ASTM F1717 at a single compressive load configuration. Environmental conditions (23°C, ambient humidity) were recorded. The achieved level is below the required level because only one test condition (compression-bending at the standard offset distance) was evaluated; no variation in load angle or offset distance was explored. This deficit is noted as a limitation of the current validation scope."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Correspondence between experimental measurements and model inputs confirmed for all load-bearing parameters; any discrepancies quantified and propagated.",
      "rationale": "All experimentally measured input parameters (geometry, material properties, torque preload) were directly mapped to model inputs with documented traceability. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that ±5% variation in friction coefficient produced less than 1.5% change in predicted yield force, supporting the equivalency claim."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison of FEA predictions to experimental measurements using pre-specified acceptance bounds.",
      "rationale": "The assessment team confirmed that predicted QoI values were compared against experimental data using the pre-specified E/uval metric and the 10% difference bound. The comparison was judged adequate for the purposes of the overall credibility determination."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are directly linked to the clinical failure modes of interest (fatigue initiation, screw fracture).",
      "rationale": "The three selected QoIs are the same quantities specified in ASTM F1717 as indicators of structural adequacy. Stiffness characterizes load sharing; yield force identifies the onset of permanent deformation; force at 40 mm displacement bounds catastrophic failure risk. All three are mechanistically linked to the clinical decision consequence."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities directly replicate the intended use scenario; geometry, loading, and boundary conditions are representative of the COU.",
      "rationale": "The validation experiment uses production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested under the identical ASTM F1717 protocol that defines the regulatory submission boundary condition. The FEA model geometry, material, and boundary conditions are derived from the same design files used for the COU prediction, establishing high relevance of the validation activity to the COU."
    }
  ],
